Elon Musk is forced to resign as chairman of Tesla’s board of directors
The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission and Tesla founder Elon Musk have settled their dispute over the fraud case.
This is reported by CNBC News.
According to the TV channel, within the framework of the agreements reached, Mask will have to leave the post of head of the board of directors of Tesla.
At the same time, the commission allowed Mask to retain the post of head of Tesla.
As noted, the founder of Tesla will also have to pay an administrative penalty of $20 million.
A similar amount will be raised with Tesla.
The money will be distributed among the affected investors.
In addition, the company must appoint two independent directors.
Elon Musk is an American entrepreneur who is one of the 50 richest people on the planet according to Forbes magazine.
He is the head of SpaceX, the neurotechnological company Neuralink, and the developer of Tesla electric cars, as well as the co-founder of Paypal.
The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission has previously referred Tesla CEO Ilona Mask to court for his tweet about the company’s possible buyout.
Last month, Musk announced plans to make Tesla a private company and buy all shares on the stock exchange at a fixed price of $420.
The stock price of $420 was set “due to the significance of this number in the marijuana culture,” Bloomberg reported earlier, citing the co-director of the Commission’s security department Steven Peykin.
At the same time, Elon Musk subsequently refused to buy the shares.
Commenting on a lawsuit filed against him by the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, the businessman said he found the allegations of fraud unfounded, adding that he was very disappointed and disappointed by these claims.
“Honesty is the most important value in my life, and the facts prove that I have not violated it in any way,” a businessman told CNBC.
At the same time, in August, a group of Tesla shareholders filed a collective lawsuit against Mask, complaining of financial losses incurred.
The Estonians claimed that the posts of the businessman brought them losses.
In particular, one of the shareholders stated that the tweets of the businessman were misleading, which forced Tesla’s stock sellers to buy paper at artificially overpriced prices to cover their positions.
Other claimants also noted that Ilona Mask’s careless statements led to sharp fluctuations in the course.
In September, Ilona Maska also accused the head of research company Citron Research in stock exchanges.
Meanwhile, if Musk could not settle his dispute with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, he would be threatened with removal from the company’s management and even prison.
This was reported by former Commission Chairman Harvey Pitt, in particular, to CNBC.
Musk is a "good guy who can't run a car company."
