AdG became the second most popular in Germany
The anti-immigrant "Alternative for Germany" beats another record of popularity, and Angela Merkel's ratings fall.
Apparently, the people of Germany began to get seriously tired of Angela Merkel’s immigration policy, which made the country a key target for millions of refugees from the Middle East.
The most obvious is the recent social questions, according to which the anti-immigrant party "Alternative for Germany" is becoming more and more popular, and the positions of the ruling bloc Merkel and Seehofer are weakening.
This week, ADG broke another record, rising to second place in the ranking of popular sympathies.
Right-wing conservatives with 17 percent of popularity managed to bypass social democrats, with about 16 percent.
The gap in one percentage point can be attributed to a statistical error, but it is worth noting the fact that the ADG created in 2013 from a small group of Eurosceptic economists has managed to turn into a serious political force.
The overall leadership is still holding the HSS/HDS ruling bloc, which has about 30 per cent.
However, there is a tendency to lose points – backing of Angela Merkel’s bloc was four percentage points higher in April.
The personal rating of the German Chancellor, who heads the German government for the fourth consecutive term, is also reduced.
Today, 48 per cent of Germans support Merkel, which is 7 per cent lower than last year.
Let’s add that the social democrats were followed by the “green” (15%), the left (11%) and the liberals (10%).
Evolution of "Alternatives"
The Alternative for Germany party was established in September 2012 on the basis of the group Alternative Choice 2013 which included the supporters of the Christian Democratic Union.
The group initially opposed the government’s course, but initially engaged only in economic issues, including the problems of the euro and interaction within the EU.
At the same time, the group opposed Germany’s “sponsoring” of weak EU economies, did not rule out the possibility of returning to the German brand and the country’s full exit from the European Union.
Against the background of the deepening of the immigration crisis, the political platform of the ADG has expanded.
In 2013, the group formed a full-fledged party, which took up a niche of Eurosceptics and began to harshly criticize the government for the failure of immigration policy.
In the last parliamentary elections in 2017, ADG managed to break into the Bundestag for the first time, receiving 94 seats (out of 709).
Two representatives of “Alternatives for Germany” received seats in the European Parliament.
