Named the time of the universe's death
The universe is about 140 billion years old, which is ten times the age of the observed world, equal to about 13.8 billion years.
The study of the international team of scientists is presented in the library of electronic preprints arXiv.org and is aimed at publication in the journal Publications of the Astronomical Society of Japan, reports the Japanese newspaper Asahi Shimbun.
Experts have come to such conclusions by observing with the help of the HSC (Hyper Suprime-Cam) Subaru telescope for about ten million galaxies.
By tracking the distribution of dark matter and dark energy, which accounts for more than 95 percent of the mass energy of the observed world, scientists, working within the standard cosmological model <0xCE><0x9B>CDM (<0xCE><0x9B> Cold Dark Matter), estimated the rate of expansion of the Universe, which was a little slower than previously thought.
The Subaru Observatory’s press release noted that observations made it possible to obtain a detailed three-dimensional map of the distribution of matter in the Universe, and the inclusion of data from the European Space Telescope Planck clarified the limitations imposed on the LCDM parameters.
In July, scientists modeled the possible demise of the universe.
Three years earlier, their colleagues presented new arguments in favor of the fact that the observed world would cease to exist 22 billion years later as a result of the Big Bang.
