U.S. Considers Russia’s Sea Blockade Due to Oil and Gas Supply
In the U.S., they could launch a naval blockade of Russia to gain an advantage in the global energy carrier market.
The U.S. authorities have fought so fiercely for the success of the global hydrocarbon market that they are ready to resort to Russia’s maritime blockade, which remains one of the world’s leading energy suppliers.
About the possibility of a sea blockade the day before, U.S. Minister of State Ryan Zinke said.
Contrary to global practice, the U.S. Department of the Interior does not perform police, but civilian functions, including implementing policies in the field of natural resources.
Therefore, Zinke’s statement was fully within the competence of the department headed by him, although the political color was not deprived.
Speaking at an industrial event in Pittsburgh, Zinke said that thanks to U.S. naval forces they control sea lanes in the Middle East region and can block them if necessary.
Zinke said the need could be linked to Washington’s desire to prevent Russian supplies to the global energy market.
Zinke recalled that Russia still receives a lion’s share of its revenues from supplies to the world oil and gas market.
The desire to distribute energy supplies in the Middle East as well as in Eastern Europe was the main motive for Moscow’s activation in this region, Zinke believes.
The minister made it clear that the United States still expects to secure leadership in the global energy market, becoming the largest supplier of oil and gas.
For this, Washington will have to push Russia and Iran, and the sea blockade of trade routes is an acceptable measure on this path, Zinke said.
