Germany's Foreign Minister Honors Victims of Nazism in Italy
In Mardsabatoto in northern Italy, an action was held in memory of the victims of the Nazi punitive operation, during which about 770 people were killed in September-October 1944.
Most of them are women and children.
This year’s ceremony was attended by German Foreign Minister Haiko Maas.
He said that “with deep sorrow and great shame” he leans towards the victims of the murder and their families.
Maas promised to oppose nationalism in the struggle for freedom, mutual respect and friendship between Italy and Germany.
Along with the German minister, his Italian colleague Enzo Moavero-Milanezi arrived in Mardsabotto.
Italy’s foreign ministry stressed that heads of foreign policy agencies are participating in the ceremony for the first time together and this symbolizes the desire of both countries to preserve memory of the crimes of the past.
