The scientist told about the possible scientific program of the expedition of the Russian Federation to the moon
The head of the Institute of Space Research of the RAN, corresponding member of the RAN Anatoly Petrukovich told RIA Novosti about a possible program of scientific research for Russian astronauts on the Moon.
According to him, the scientific community is now developing directions for such works.
“There is no consolidated opinion yet,” the scientist said.
He noted that one of the options is the placement of a low-frequency radio telescope on the opposite side of the Moon, which would avoid interference, the source of which is Earth.
“This is the only place where such a telescope can be deployed to study space sources of radiation,” Petrukovich added.
He also believes that the Moon could be used to conduct robotics tests, to use local resources for construction.
In addition, cosmonauts should be attracted to the search for primitive organics on Earth's satellite, according to the scientist.
This could help determine how life appears on the planets.
Earlier, the head of the Roscosmos Corporation said that in an optimistic version, the Russian Federation can carry out a piloted flight to the moon by 2030.
