The Macedonians are preparing to vote in a referendum on joining the EU and NATO on the condition that the country’s name is changed.
The agreement on the renaming of the former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia to the Republic of North Macedonia was reached on June 17 as a result of long negotiations with neighbouring Greece, which refused to recognize its northern neighbor the right to be called Macedonia, observing the same name in the same name.
Lupko Petkovsky, political scientist: “With this agreement, Macedonia or North Macedonia gets the right to a better future, the hope for social change.
And Greece will secure the right to its past.
There are no perfect agreements.
They arise as a result of difficult compromises that can’t satisfy absolutely everyone.”
The country is renamed by the ruling Social Democrats headed by Prime Minister Zoran Zaev.
The opposition is the conservative opposition and the president of the country George Ivanov.
According to journalist Tsvetin Chilimanov, Macedonia does not make sense to join the EU - it is enough to have a partnership with him: "Many of those who do not like the agreement believe that the current socialist government headed by Zaev is forced from abroad to change the name.
